{"paragraphs":[{"cues":[{"time":1000,"text":"Welcome. If I could have the first slide, please?"},{"time":15000,"text":"Contrary to calculations made by some engineers, bees can fly,"},{"time":20000,"text":"dolphins can swim, and geckos can even climb"},{"time":27000,"text":"up the smoothest surfaces. Now, what I want to do, in the short time I have,"},{"time":33000,"text":"is to try to allow each of you to experience"},{"time":37000,"text":"the thrill of revealing nature's design."},{"time":43000,"text":"I get to do this all the time, and it's just incredible."},{"time":45000,"text":"I want to try to share just a little bit of that with you in this presentation."},{"time":51000,"text":"The challenge of looking at nature's designs --"},{"time":53000,"text":"and I'll tell you the way that we perceive it, and the way we've used it."},{"time":57000,"text":"The challenge, of course, is to answer this question:"},{"time":59000,"text":"what permits this extraordinary performance of animals"},{"time":62000,"text":"that allows them basically to go anywhere?"},{"time":65000,"text":"And if we could figure that out, how can we implement those designs?"}]},{"cues":[{"time":72000,"text":"Well, many biologists will tell engineers, and others,"},{"time":75000,"text":"organisms have millions of years to get it right;"},{"time":78000,"text":"they're spectacular; they can do everything wonderfully well."},{"time":81000,"text":"So, the answer is bio-mimicry: just copy nature directly."},{"time":85000,"text":"We know from working on animals that the truth is"},{"time":90000,"text":"that's exactly what you don't want to do -- because evolution works"},{"time":94000,"text":"on the just-good-enough principle, not on a perfecting principle."},{"time":97000,"text":"And the constraints in building any organism, when you look at it,"},{"time":101000,"text":"are really severe. Natural technologies have incredible constraints."},{"time":106000,"text":"Think about it. If you were an engineer and I told you"},{"time":109000,"text":"that you had to build an automobile, but it had to start off to be this big,"},{"time":114000,"text":"then it had to grow to be full size and had to work every step along the way."},{"time":118000,"text":"Or think about the fact that if you build an automobile, I'll tell you that you also -- inside it --"},{"time":122000,"text":"have to put a factory that allows you to make another automobile."}]},{"cues":[{"time":126000,"text":"(Laughter)"}]},{"cues":[{"time":128000,"text":"And you can absolutely never, absolutely never, because of history"},{"time":132000,"text":"and the inherited plan, start with a clean slate."},{"time":136000,"text":"So, organisms have this important history."},{"time":139000,"text":"Really evolution works more like a tinkerer than an engineer."},{"time":144000,"text":"And this is really important when you begin to look at animals."},{"time":147000,"text":"Instead, we believe you need to be inspired by biology."},{"time":154000,"text":"You need to discover the general principles of nature,"},{"time":158000,"text":"and then use these analogies when they're advantageous."},{"time":164000,"text":"This is a real challenge to do this, because animals,"},{"time":167000,"text":"when you start to really look inside them -- how they work --"},{"time":170000,"text":"appear hopelessly complex. There's no detailed history"},{"time":174000,"text":"of the design plans, you can't go look it up anywhere."},{"time":177000,"text":"They have way too many motions for their joints, too many muscles."},{"time":181000,"text":"Even the simplest animal we think of, something like an insect,"},{"time":184000,"text":"and they have more neurons and connections than you can imagine."}]},{"cues":[{"time":187000,"text":"How can you make sense of this? Well, we believed --"},{"time":192000,"text":"and we hypothesized -- that one way animals could work simply,"},{"time":197000,"text":"is if the control of their movements"},{"time":200000,"text":"tended to be built into their bodies themselves."},{"time":206000,"text":"What we discovered was that two-, four-, six- and eight-legged animals"},{"time":213000,"text":"all produce the same forces on the ground when they move."},{"time":216000,"text":"They all work like this kangaroo, they bounce."},{"time":220000,"text":"And they can be modeled by a spring-mass system that we call the spring mass system"},{"time":224000,"text":"because we're biomechanists. It's actually a pogo stick."},{"time":227000,"text":"They all produce the pattern of a pogo stick. How is that true?"},{"time":231000,"text":"Well, a human, one of your legs works like two legs of a trotting dog,"},{"time":237000,"text":"or works like three legs, together as one, of a trotting insect,"},{"time":241000,"text":"or four legs as one of a trotting crab."},{"time":243000,"text":"And then they alternate in their propulsion,"},{"time":247000,"text":"but the patterns are all the same. Almost every organism we've looked at this way"},{"time":252000,"text":"-- you'll see next week, I'll give you a hint,"},{"time":254000,"text":"there'll be an article coming out that says that really big things"},{"time":257000,"text":"like T. rex probably couldn't do this, but you'll see that next week."}]},{"cues":[{"time":261000,"text":"Now, what's interesting is the animals, then -- we said -- bounce along"},{"time":263000,"text":"the vertical plane this way, and in our collaborations with Pixar,"},{"time":266000,"text":"in \"A Bug's Life,\" we discussed the"},{"time":268000,"text":"bipedal nature of the characters of the ants."},{"time":271000,"text":"And we told them, of course, they move in another plane as well."},{"time":273000,"text":"And they asked us this question. They say, \"Why model"},{"time":276000,"text":"just in the sagittal plane or the vertical plane,"},{"time":278000,"text":"when you're telling us these animals are moving"},{"time":280000,"text":"in the horizontal plane?\" This is a good question."},{"time":283000,"text":"Nobody in biology ever modeled it this way."},{"time":286000,"text":"We took their advice and we modeled the animals moving"},{"time":290000,"text":"in the horizontal plane as well. We took their three legs,"},{"time":293000,"text":"we collapsed them down as one."},{"time":294000,"text":"We got some of the best mathematicians in the world"},{"time":297000,"text":"from Princeton to work on this problem."},{"time":299000,"text":"And we were able to create a model"},{"time":302000,"text":"where animals are not only bouncing up and down,"},{"time":303000,"text":"but they're also bouncing side to side at the same time."},{"time":307000,"text":"And many organisms fit this kind of pattern."},{"time":309000,"text":"Now, why is this important to have this model?"},{"time":311000,"text":"Because it's very interesting. When you take this model"},{"time":314000,"text":"and you perturb it, you give it a push,"},{"time":317000,"text":"as it bumps into something, it self-stabilizes, with no brain"},{"time":321000,"text":"or no reflexes, just by the structure alone."},{"time":325000,"text":"It's a beautiful model. Let's look at the mathematics."}]},{"cues":[{"time":330000,"text":"(Laughter)"}]},{"cues":[{"time":332000,"text":"That's enough!"}]},{"cues":[{"time":333000,"text":"(Laughter)"}]},{"cues":[{"time":337000,"text":"The animals, when you look at them running,"},{"time":339000,"text":"appear to be self-stabilizing like this,"},{"time":342000,"text":"using basically springy legs. That is, the legs can do"},{"time":345000,"text":"computations on their own; the control algorithms, in a sense,"},{"time":348000,"text":"are embedded in the form of the animal itself."},{"time":351000,"text":"Why haven't we been more inspired by nature and these kinds of discoveries?"},{"time":358000,"text":"Well, I would argue that human technologies are really different from"},{"time":362000,"text":"natural technologies, at least they have been so far."},{"time":365000,"text":"Think about the typical kind of robot that you see."},{"time":370000,"text":"Human technologies have tended to be large, flat,"},{"time":373000,"text":"with right angles, stiff, made of metal. They have rolling devices"},{"time":378000,"text":"and axles. There are very few motors, very few sensors."},{"time":381000,"text":"Whereas nature tends to be small, and curved,"},{"time":386000,"text":"and it bends and twists, and has legs instead, and appendages,"},{"time":389000,"text":"and has many muscles and many, many sensors."},{"time":392000,"text":"So it's a very different design. However, what's changing,"},{"time":396000,"text":"what's really exciting -- and I'll show you some of that next --"},{"time":398000,"text":"is that as human technology takes on more of the characteristics"},{"time":401000,"text":"of nature, then nature really can become a much more useful teacher."}]},{"cues":[{"time":407000,"text":"And here's one example that's really exciting."},{"time":409000,"text":"This is a collaboration we have with Stanford."},{"time":411000,"text":"And they developed this new technique, called Shape Deposition Manufacturing."},{"time":415000,"text":"It's a technique where they can mix materials together and mold any shape"},{"time":419000,"text":"that they like, and put in the material properties."},{"time":423000,"text":"They can embed sensors and actuators right in the form itself."},{"time":426000,"text":"For example, here's a leg: the clear part is stiff,"},{"time":431000,"text":"the white part is compliant, and you don't need any axles there or anything."},{"time":434000,"text":"It just bends by itself beautifully."},{"time":437000,"text":"So, you can put those properties in. It inspired them to show off"},{"time":440000,"text":"this design by producing a little robot they named Sprawl."},{"time":446000,"text":"Our work has also inspired another robot, a biologically inspired bouncing robot,"},{"time":450000,"text":"from the University of Michigan and McGill"},{"time":452000,"text":"named RHex, for robot hexapod, and this one's autonomous."},{"time":460000,"text":"Let's go to the video, and let me show you some of these animals moving"},{"time":463000,"text":"and then some of the simple robots"},{"time":465000,"text":"that have been inspired by our discoveries."},{"time":468000,"text":"Here's what some of you did this morning, although you did it outside,"},{"time":472000,"text":"not on a treadmill."},{"time":474000,"text":"Here's what we do."}]},{"cues":[{"time":477000,"text":"(Laughter)"}]},{"cues":[{"time":479000,"text":"This is a death's head cockroach. This is an American cockroach"},{"time":484000,"text":"you think you don't have in your kitchen."},{"time":485000,"text":"This is an eight-legged scorpion, six-legged ant, forty-four-legged centipede."},{"time":492000,"text":"Now, I said all these animals are sort of working like pogo sticks --"},{"time":495000,"text":"they're bouncing along as they move. And you can see that"},{"time":499000,"text":"in this ghost crab, from the beaches of Panama and North Carolina."},{"time":502000,"text":"It goes up to four meters per second when it runs."},{"time":505000,"text":"It actually leaps into the air, and has aerial phases"},{"time":508000,"text":"when it does it, like a horse, and you'll see it's bouncing here."},{"time":512000,"text":"What we discovered is whether you look at the leg of a human"},{"time":515000,"text":"like Richard, or a cockroach, or a crab, or a kangaroo,"},{"time":521000,"text":"the relative leg stiffness of that spring is the same for everything we've seen so far."},{"time":526000,"text":"Now, what good are springy legs then? What can they do?"},{"time":528000,"text":"Well, we wanted to see if they allowed the animals"},{"time":530000,"text":"to have greater stability and maneuverability."},{"time":533000,"text":"So, we built a terrain that had obstacles three times the hip height"},{"time":537000,"text":"of the animals that we're looking at."},{"time":538000,"text":"And we were certain they couldn't do this. And here's what they did."},{"time":542000,"text":"The animal ran over it and it didn't even slow down!"},{"time":545000,"text":"It didn't decrease its preferred speed at all."},{"time":547000,"text":"We couldn't believe that it could do this. It said to us"},{"time":550000,"text":"that if you could build a robot with very simple, springy legs,"},{"time":555000,"text":"you could make it as maneuverable as any that's ever been built."}]},{"cues":[{"time":561000,"text":"Here's the first example of that. This is the Stanford"},{"time":563000,"text":"Shape Deposition Manufactured robot, named Sprawl."},{"time":566000,"text":"It has six legs -- there are the tuned, springy legs."},{"time":572000,"text":"It moves in a gait that an insect uses, and here it is"},{"time":575000,"text":"going on the treadmill. Now, what's important about this robot,"},{"time":582000,"text":"compared to other robots, is that it can't see anything,"},{"time":585000,"text":"it can't feel anything, it doesn't have a brain, yet it can maneuver"},{"time":591000,"text":"over these obstacles without any difficulty whatsoever."},{"time":597000,"text":"It's this technique of building the properties into the form."},{"time":601000,"text":"This is a graduate student. This is what he's doing to his thesis project --"},{"time":604000,"text":"very robust, if a graduate student"},{"time":606000,"text":"does that to his thesis project."}]},{"cues":[{"time":608000,"text":"(Laughter)"}]},{"cues":[{"time":609000,"text":"This is from McGill and University of Michigan. This is the RHex,"},{"time":613000,"text":"making its first outing in a demo."}]},{"cues":[{"time":616000,"text":"(Laughter)"}]},{"cues":[{"time":620000,"text":"Same principle: it only has six moving parts,"},{"time":625000,"text":"six motors, but it has springy, tuned legs. It moves in the gait of the insect."},{"time":631000,"text":"It has the middle leg moving in synchrony with the front,"},{"time":635000,"text":"and the hind leg on the other side. Sort of an alternating tripod,"},{"time":639000,"text":"and they can negotiate obstacles just like the animal."}]},{"cues":[{"time":643000,"text":"(Laughter)"}]},{"cues":[{"time":649000,"text":"(Voice: Oh my God.)"}]},{"cues":[{"time":650000,"text":"(Applause)"}]},{"cues":[{"time":655000,"text":"Robert Full: It'll go on different surfaces -- here's sand --"},{"time":657000,"text":"although we haven't perfected the feet yet, but I'll talk about that later."},{"time":662000,"text":"Here's RHex entering the woods."}]},{"cues":[{"time":665000,"text":"(Laughter)"}]},{"cues":[{"time":680000,"text":"Again, this robot can't see anything, it can't feel anything,"},{"time":684000,"text":"it has no brain. It's just working with a tuned mechanical system,"},{"time":690000,"text":"with very simple parts, but inspired from the fundamental dynamics of the animal."},{"time":700000,"text":"(Voice: Ah, I love him, Bob.) RF: Here's it going down a pathway."},{"time":708000,"text":"I presented this to the jet propulsion lab at NASA, and they said"},{"time":711000,"text":"that they had no ability to go down craters to look for ice,"},{"time":715000,"text":"and life, ultimately, on Mars. And he said --"},{"time":719000,"text":"especially with legged-robots, because they're way too complicated."},{"time":721000,"text":"Nothing can do that. And I talk next. I showed them this video"},{"time":726000,"text":"with the simple design of RHex here. And just to convince them"},{"time":729000,"text":"we should go to Mars in 2011, I tinted the video orange"},{"time":733000,"text":"just to give them the sense of being on Mars."}]},{"cues":[{"time":736000,"text":"(Laughter)"}]},{"cues":[{"time":737000,"text":"(Applause)"}]},{"cues":[{"time":745000,"text":"Another reason why animals have extraordinary performance,"},{"time":748000,"text":"and can go anywhere, is because they have an effective interaction"},{"time":751000,"text":"with the environment. The animal I'm going to show you,"},{"time":754000,"text":"that we studied to look at this, is the gecko."},{"time":758000,"text":"We have one here and notice its position. It's holding on."},{"time":765000,"text":"Now I'm going to challenge you. I'm going show you a video."},{"time":768000,"text":"One of the animals is going to be running on the level,"},{"time":770000,"text":"and the other one's going to be running up a wall. Which one's which?"},{"time":774000,"text":"They're going at a meter a second. How many think the one on the left"},{"time":779000,"text":"is running up the wall?"}]},{"cues":[{"time":781000,"text":"(Applause)"}]},{"cues":[{"time":785000,"text":"Okay. The point is it's really hard to tell, isn't it? It's incredible,"},{"time":790000,"text":"we looked at students do this and they couldn't tell."},{"time":792000,"text":"They can run up a wall at a meter a second, 15 steps per second,"},{"time":795000,"text":"and they look like they're running on the level. How do they do this?"},{"time":799000,"text":"It's just phenomenal. The one on the right was going up the hill."},{"time":805000,"text":"How do they do this? They have bizarre toes. They have toes"},{"time":809000,"text":"that uncurl like party favors when you blow them out,"},{"time":813000,"text":"and then peel off the surface, like tape."},{"time":816000,"text":"Like if we had a piece of tape now, we'd peel it this way."},{"time":818000,"text":"They do this with their toes. It's bizarre! This peeling inspired"},{"time":825000,"text":"iRobot -- that we work with -- to build Mecho-Geckos."},{"time":828000,"text":"Here's a legged version and a tractor version, or a bulldozer version."},{"time":835000,"text":"Let's see some of the geckos move with some video,"},{"time":837000,"text":"and then I'll show you a little bit of a clip of the robots."},{"time":840000,"text":"Here's the gecko running up a vertical surface. There it goes,"},{"time":843000,"text":"in real time. There it goes again. Obviously, we have to slow this down a little bit."}]},{"cues":[{"time":850000,"text":"You can't use regular cameras."},{"time":852000,"text":"You have to take 1,000 pictures per second to see this."},{"time":855000,"text":"And here's some video at 1,000 frames per second."},{"time":858000,"text":"Now, I want you to look at the animal's back."},{"time":860000,"text":"Do you see how much it's bending like that? We can't figure that out --"},{"time":863000,"text":"that's an unsolved mystery. We don't know how it works."},{"time":866000,"text":"If you have a son or a daughter that wants to come to Berkeley,"},{"time":869000,"text":"come to my lab and we'll figure this out. Okay, send them to Berkeley"},{"time":873000,"text":"because that's the next thing I want to do. Here's the gecko mill."}]},{"cues":[{"time":876000,"text":"(Laughter)"}]},{"cues":[{"time":877000,"text":"It's a see-through treadmill with a see-through treadmill belt,"},{"time":880000,"text":"so we can watch the animal's feet, and videotape them"},{"time":883000,"text":"through the treadmill belt, to see how they move."},{"time":886000,"text":"Here's the animal that we have here, running on a vertical surface."},{"time":890000,"text":"Pick a foot and try to watch a toe, and see if you can see what the animal's doing."},{"time":896000,"text":"See it uncurl and then peel these toes."},{"time":898000,"text":"It can do this in 14 milliseconds. It's unbelievable."},{"time":905000,"text":"Here are the robots that they inspire, the Mecho-Geckos from iRobot."},{"time":909000,"text":"First we'll see the animals toes peeling -- look at that."},{"time":914000,"text":"And here's the peeling action of the Mecho-Gecko."},{"time":918000,"text":"It uses a pressure-sensitive adhesive to do it."},{"time":921000,"text":"Peeling in the animal. Peeling in the Mecho-Gecko --"},{"time":924000,"text":"that allows them climb autonomously. Can go on the flat surface,"},{"time":927000,"text":"transition to a wall, and then go onto a ceiling."},{"time":930000,"text":"There's the bulldozer version. Now, it doesn't use pressure-sensitive glue."},{"time":936000,"text":"The animal does not use that."},{"time":938000,"text":"But that's what we're limited to, at the moment."}]},{"cues":[{"time":940000,"text":"What does the animal do? The animal has weird toes."},{"time":945000,"text":"And if you look at the toes, they have these little leaves there,"},{"time":949000,"text":"and if you blow them up and zoom in, you'll see"},{"time":951000,"text":"that's there's little striations in these leaves."},{"time":954000,"text":"And if you zoom in 270 times, you'll see it looks like a rug."},{"time":961000,"text":"And if you blow that up, and zoom in 900 times,"},{"time":964000,"text":"you see there are hairs there, tiny hairs. And if you look carefully,"},{"time":969000,"text":"those tiny hairs have striations. And if you zoom in on those 30,000 times,"},{"time":975000,"text":"you'll see each hair has split ends."},{"time":978000,"text":"And if you blow those up, they have these little structures on the end."},{"time":983000,"text":"The smallest branch of the hairs looks like spatulae,"},{"time":985000,"text":"and an animal like that has one billion of these nano-size split ends,"},{"time":992000,"text":"to get very close to the surface. In fact, there's the diameter of your hair --"},{"time":997000,"text":"a gecko has two million of these, and each hair has 100 to 1,000 split ends."},{"time":1003000,"text":"Think of the contact of that that's possible."}]},{"cues":[{"time":1006000,"text":"We were fortunate to work with another group"},{"time":1008000,"text":"at Stanford that built us a special manned sensor,"},{"time":1010000,"text":"that we were able to measure the force of an individual hair."},{"time":1013000,"text":"Here's an individual hair with a little split end there."},{"time":1018000,"text":"When we measured the forces, they were enormous."},{"time":1020000,"text":"They were so large that a patch of hairs about this size --"},{"time":1023000,"text":"the gecko's foot could support the weight of a small child,"},{"time":1027000,"text":"about 40 pounds, easily. Now, how do they do it?"},{"time":1031000,"text":"We've recently discovered this. Do they do it by friction?"},{"time":1035000,"text":"No, force is too low. Do they do it by electrostatics?"},{"time":1038000,"text":"No, you can change the charge -- they still hold on."},{"time":1040000,"text":"Do they do it by interlocking? That's kind of a like a Velcro-like thing."},{"time":1043000,"text":"No, you can put them on molecular smooth surfaces -- they don't do it."},{"time":1046000,"text":"How about suction? They stick on in a vacuum."},{"time":1050000,"text":"How about wet adhesion? Or capillary adhesion?"},{"time":1053000,"text":"They don't have any glue, and they even stick under water just fine."},{"time":1056000,"text":"If you put their foot under water, they grab on."},{"time":1058000,"text":"How do they do it then? Believe it or not, they grab on"},{"time":1062000,"text":"by intermolecular forces, by Van der Waals forces."}]},{"cues":[{"time":1066000,"text":"You know, you probably had this a long time ago in chemistry,"},{"time":1068000,"text":"where you had these two atoms, they're close together,"},{"time":1070000,"text":"and the electrons are moving around. That tiny force is sufficient"},{"time":1073000,"text":"to allow them to do that because it's added up so many times"},{"time":1076000,"text":"with these small structures."},{"time":1079000,"text":"What we're doing is, we're taking that inspiration of the hairs,"},{"time":1084000,"text":"and with another colleague at Berkeley, we're manufacturing them."},{"time":1089000,"text":"And just recently we've made a breakthrough, where we now believe"},{"time":1092000,"text":"we're going to be able to create the first synthetic, self-cleaning,"},{"time":1097000,"text":"dry adhesive. Many companies are interested in this."}]},{"cues":[{"time":1102000,"text":"(Laughter)"}]},{"cues":[{"time":1105000,"text":"We also presented to Nike even."}]},{"cues":[{"time":1107000,"text":"(Laughter)"}]},{"cues":[{"time":1110000,"text":"(Applause)"}]},{"cues":[{"time":1116000,"text":"We'll see where this goes. We were so excited about this"},{"time":1119000,"text":"that we realized that that small-size scale --"},{"time":1122000,"text":"and where everything gets sticky, and gravity doesn't matter anymore --"},{"time":1125000,"text":"we needed to look at ants and their feet, because"},{"time":1128000,"text":"one of my other colleagues at Berkeley has built a six-millimeter silicone"},{"time":1133000,"text":"robot with legs. But it gets stuck. It doesn't move very well."},{"time":1136000,"text":"But the ants do, and we'll figure out why, so that ultimately"},{"time":1139000,"text":"we'll make this move. And imagine: you're going to be able"},{"time":1142000,"text":"to have swarms of these six-millimeter robots available to run around."},{"time":1147000,"text":"Where's this going? I think you can see it already."}]},{"cues":[{"time":1150000,"text":"Clearly, the Internet is already having eyes and ears,"},{"time":1154000,"text":"you have web cams and so forth. But it's going to also have legs and hands."},{"time":1158000,"text":"You're going to be able to do programmable"},{"time":1160000,"text":"work through these kinds of robots, so that you can run,"},{"time":1164000,"text":"fly and swim anywhere. We saw David Kelly is at the beginning of that with his fish."},{"time":1173000,"text":"So, in conclusion, I think the message is clear."},{"time":1175000,"text":"If you need a message, if nature's not enough, if you care about"},{"time":1179000,"text":"search and rescue, or mine clearance, or medicine,"},{"time":1181000,"text":"or the various things we're working on, we must preserve"},{"time":1185000,"text":"nature's designs, otherwise these secrets will be lost forever."},{"time":1189000,"text":"Thank you."}]},{"cues":[{"time":1190000,"text":"(Applause)"}]}]}